prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: CCOSMOS X-ray selected AGN with z=2-2.3
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
The objectives of this proposal is to determine the star formation rate of X-ray selected quasars. This science goal contains 59 X-ray selected AGN with L_x > 10^43.5 erg/s in a redshift range z=2-2.3.
The requested observations are to reach a 1sigma rms sensitivity of 0.2 mJy in band 7 continuum mode.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Requested sensitivity: In order to detect a source with Lfir ~ 8x10^11 Lsun (with T=40K and beta=1.5) at redshift z=2, at a 4sigma level in band 7, we need a sensitivity of 1sigma rms = 0.2 mJy at 344 GHz. This is achievable within 1.2 min per source. Our full sample counts 59 sources with X-ray luminosity Lx > 10^43.5 erg/s and a redshift range z=2-2.3. Selected from the C-COSMOS survey. The total estimated time for the full sample including calibration and overheads is 2.6 hours.
Correlator setup: The objective is to measure the 344 continuum flux for the full sample. We therefore request continuum mode using the default frequency.
Imaging requirements: This project aims to detect the individual sources. We do have any specific imaging requirements. We expect all sources to be point sources, however, as the emission potentially could extended over 1-2 kpc (0.1-0.2arcsec) we have chosen "extended source with 0.4 arcsec". This project could be carried out for any configuration that allows for an angular resolution > 0.4".

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Bright powerful AGN at high-z represent a phase of intense growth of the super-massive black holes. Quasars and powerful AGN feedback has been suggested to both quench and enhance star formation in their host galaxies. Two recent studies of star formation in the host galaxies of powerful AGN reached different conclusions. Page et al (2012) on a smaller sample concluded that the powerful AGN suppress the star formation. However Harrison et al (2012) using a much larger sample could not reach that conclusion, finding that the average star formation rate did not seem related to the X-ray luminosity. In both studies the results were derived through stacking of Herschel PACS data. In this proposal, we address the question, is star formation suppressed by powerful AGN, exploring the great sensitivity and arcsec resolution capabilities of ALMA. We have selected a sample of 59 X-ray bright AGN from the C-COSMOS survey with luminosity Lx>10^43. We selected the quasars in a narrow redshift range z=2-2.3 to avoid cosmological evolutionary effects impacting on the results. We aim for to be able to detect SFR to the level of 100 M/yr, which is below the average SFR~150-200 My/yr.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
